Since the release of the HTC EVO 4G, I had used LauncherPro as my launcher of choice. After a promise of a "complete rewriting of the app," that launcher seems to have been abandoned for almost a year now and has since then shown signs of it (e.g. slow performance, unidentifiable FCs). I should have switched launchers a long time ago, since there are features in this one that are far superior to LP. Screen transitions are much smoother, and the homescreens/app drawer are much easier to customize (I love the ability to create folders just by placing an app on top of another on the homescreens). Themes are extremely easy to apply, and there appear to be an abundance of them available in the Play store. No cons to report, although I would like to see a feature to prevent some apps from showing up in the app drawer (like carrier-specific apps that many people never use or stock apps that have been replaced by 3rd-party apps), as well as an ICS screen transition implemented to match the other ICS-inspired customizations. Overall, a great buy and excellent replacement for your stock/current launcher.

*Uninstalled*  After installing it on my TMo G2 CM7 (v7.1.0), my phone took a significant hit to performance and stability most notably Google Navigation.  Google Navigation wasn't able to display the maps up to the minute which can make the difference of missing a turn.  Other applications such as FaceBook and Dolphin Browser began displaying Force Close notifications.  What really forced me to finally remove this application off of my phone was the fact that stability issues began to grow more prominent with CM7 itself!    It is clear that this application is a resource hog and now can understand the old threads on XDA recommending AGAINST this application.  I had believed that the developer for this application had since solved these issues, but alas, I was wrong.  Having used this for one month while running this on my production phone, I can honestly say that I will not be using this application, at least on single core devices.  It was worth spending a dime to learn my lesson.  I will however give them credit for a beautiful interface but at the price of stability and performance, it is not worth it.    In close, if you have a single core device, don't bother.

The home screen customization has everything I want, like looping screens, gesture support, and lots of dock options. It is nice and functional even on my slow LG Optimus V, with good screen scrolling. There are lots of nice looking themes available for it.  It's really 4.5 stars for me, but I'm rounding up: the app drawer's categories are so fiddly to set up, having to screen through a list of all of the apps (instead of being able to set it to show, for instance, all uncategorized apps), that I can't use that feature even though I don't want to, because it's simply too much micromanaging; I'm using another app organizer instead, but I'd rather use the drawer in ADW. First launcher I was tempted to use (price & good reviews). Was skeptical would be different from the base phone interface. Have been using ADW for a full day & have all the tweaks in place that I wanted. The experience in adjusting to the launcher has been very smooth. The learning curve was short. Agree with others that there could be better explanation of settings. Not so much in the overall interface but in getting certain deep menu custom settings done, especially putting deep system setting icons on the launch pages. Haven't tried themes yet. Pros: Finally I can resize any widget. Google search widget on the stock interface was especially irritating to me as it didn't allow resizing. ADW solved that. Big relief. So it's the little tweaks that are rewarding. Not necessarily a big change in experience. Having more control. Adding or removing pages, extra nice. Runs smooth. No problems, battery,boot, or live wallpaper so far. Very stable. Cons: Appreciation of what the app can do for a user depends on how much you want to make small changes. Touch sensitivity when dealing with icons is iffy when doing initial set up. Not as easy to hit those arrows as stock. As normal once set.
The website only has a blog, & there is minimal in-app help.Are we supposed to be psychic? I've better things to do with my time than figure this out.

MOTOBLUR users should know that this launcher will overtake your home button, and even when you have closed ADW (by going to Settings-Applications-ManageApplications and force stopping ADW from there - look in "All apps", it doesn't show as running), pressing home will launch ADW back. So no way to use the home button when you are in the default launcher. This appears to be a Motoblur issue which I guess hides its "Home" not only from plain view, but also from other apps, and prevents them from messing with it. The app Home Switcher will NOT work - it crashes when trying to set motoblur's "Home" as default. "Clear defaults" in "Manage Apps - ADW" does NOT work, it's greyed out. When I installed another launcher, the option to choose default (on pressing home) reappeared, but it doesn't show Motorola's "Home", only ADW and the other home replacement. The developer has to be aware of that. I gather there are quite a number of Motoblurred phones around. Devs shouldn't write their apps only for the CM-blessed folk. (No, I don't want CM).

Like so many others, I updated to v1.3.3.55 and immediately complained about the lack of the hidden dockbar. I thought it was extremely useful and couldn't understand why it was removed. Then I figured out that the developers incorporated the concept of the hidden dockbar into the main dockbar. If you notice, the main dockbar now looks like what the hidden one used to look like. In previous versions, a second dockbar would appear & disappear when you swipe up & down. Now, you can swipe left & right to move between additional dockbars, similar to additional homescreens (except that the dockbars don't loop around infinitely - a feature I hope is added soon). All you need to do is add app icons to the dockbar and you'll get a second, third, etc dockbar. And they cleverly included an option in the settings so that when you open an app in the secondary dockbars, the dockbar returns to the first set of app icons. Genius.  I love this version now.
